\parindent 0pt \parskip 3pt
\vspace{-20pt}

This note expands on and analyzes some aspects of pre-frequency-averaging.

Consider the frequency-averaged radiance from one channel

\begin{equation}
I \approx\ \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \Delta B_{in}
 \tau_{in} \Delta \nu_n \text{ where }
\tau_{in} =\; \exp\left(-\sum_{j=2}^i \sum_{k=1}^{N_l} \delta_{jkn}\right)\;,
\end{equation}

$n$ indexes frequencies within the channel, $i$ and $j$ index path positions,
$k$ indexes spectral lines, and $\phi_n$ is the filter function for the
$n^\text{th}$ frequency in the channel.  If we divide the transmission $\tau$
into factors that are due to strong lines and weak lines, and expand the
exponential function of the incremental transmittance for the weak lines using
two terms of a Taylor series, we have

\begin{equation}\begin{split}
I \approx\;& \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \Delta B_{in}
 \tau_{in}^s
 \left(1-\sum_{j=2}^i
  \sum_{k \in \text{weak}} \delta_{jkn}\right) \Delta \nu_n \text{ where}\\
\tau_{in}^s =\;& \exp\left(-\sum_{j=2}^i \sum_{k \in \text{strong}}
 \delta_{jkn}\right)\;.
\end{split}\end{equation}

Expanding this we have

\begin{equation}\begin{split}\label{split}
I \approx\;& I_s - \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \Delta B_{in}
 \tau_{in}^s
\sum_{j=2}^i
  \sum_{k \in \text{weak}} \delta_{jkn} \Delta \nu_n \text{ where}\\
I_s =\;& \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \Delta B_{in} \tau_{in}^s \Delta
  \nu_n\;.
\end{split}\end{equation}

We would like to average the contributions from strong lines and weak lines
within the channel separately, giving

\begin{equation}\label{exchanged}
I \approx\; I_s - \left( \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \Delta B_{in} \phi_n
 \tau_{in}^s \Delta \nu_n \right)
  \left( \sum_{j=2}^i \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \Delta \nu_n
  \sum_{k \in \text{weak}} \delta_{jkn} \right)\;.
\end{equation}

The differential Planck radiation function $\Delta B_{in}$ changes very slowly
with frequency in our frequency range, so we replace it with a channel average
$\overline{\Delta B_i}$:

\begin{equation}\label{exchanged2}
I \approx\; I_s - \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \overline{\Delta B_i}
 \left( \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \tau_{in}^s \Delta \nu_n \right)
  \left( \sum_{j=2}^i \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \Delta \nu_n
  \sum_{k \in \text{weak}} \delta_{jkn} \right)\;.
\end{equation}

We can get some insight into the error introduced by the approximation in
Equation (\ref{exchanged}) by considering the (normalized) averages

\begin{equation}\label{averages}
A_1 =\; \frac{\sum_i w_i a_i b_i}{\sum_i w_i},\;
A_2 =\; \frac{\sum_i w_i a_i}{\sum_i w_i} \text{ and }
A_3 =\; \frac{\sum_i w_i b_i}{\sum_i w_i}
\end{equation}

and the answer to the question ``What is $\left|\left(\sum_i w_i \right)^2
\left(A_1 - A_2 A_3\right)\right|$?''  Since in our case, $0 \leq w_i < 1$ and
$\sum_i w_i = 1$, we can simplify this to

\begin{equation}\label{eterm}
\left|A_1 - A_2 A_3\right| =
\left| \sum_i \sum_{j=1}^{i-1} (a_i-a_j)(b_i-b_j)w_i w_j \right| \leq
\sum_i \sum_{j=1}^{i-1} |a_i-a_j|\,|b_i-b_j|w_i w_j\;.
\end{equation}

Thus if $|a_i-a_j|$ and $|b_i-b_j|$ are sufficiently small, the right-hand-side
of Equation (\ref{eterm}) will be small.  In particular, if
$|\delta_{jkn_1}-\delta_{jkn_2}|$ is small for all pairs $1 \leq n_1 < n_2 \leq
N_f$, the error introduced will be small.  If we define ``weak spectral lines''
in these terms, Equation (\ref{exchanged}) should not be a problem.  Returning
to Equation (\ref{exchanged2}) and letting

\begin{equation}
\overline{\tau_i^s} =\; \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n \tau_{in}^s \Delta \nu_n
\text{ and }
\overline{\delta_i} =\; \sum_{j=2}^i \sum_{n=1}^{N_f} \phi_n
  \Delta \nu_n \sum_{k \in \text{weak}} \delta_{jkn}
\end{equation}

we have

\begin{equation}
I \approx\; I_s - \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \overline{\Delta B_i}\,
         \overline{\tau_i^s}\, \overline{\delta_i}\;.
\end{equation}

Exchanging the order of summation in the definition of $I_s$ in Equation
(\ref{split}), applying the same argument to $\Delta B_{in}$, and substituting
$\overline{\tau_i^s}$, we have

\begin{equation}
I \approx\; \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \overline{\Delta B_i}\, \overline{\tau_i^s}
  - \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \overline{\Delta B_i}\,
         \overline{\tau_i^s}\, \overline{\delta_i} =
 \sum_{i=1}^{2N_p} \overline{\Delta B_i}\, \overline{\tau_i^s} ( 1 -
   \overline{\delta_i} )\;.
\end{equation}

The quantity $\overline{\Delta B_i}$ can be adequately approximated by
evaluating $\Delta B_i$ at the channel center frequency.  The quantities
$\overline{\delta_i}$ can be computed off line, separately for each species,
pressure and temperature.  The quantities $\overline{\tau_i^s}$ are computed on
line, from the quantities $\tau_{in}^s$, $\phi_n$ and $\Delta \nu_n$.

